  "prompt": "What is the difference between norco and hydrocodone?",
  "response": "Norco and hydrocodone are closely related but not identical terms. Here\u2019s a breakdown of their differences:\n\n1. **Hydrocodone**: \n   - This is an opioid pain medication that is used to treat moderate to severe pain. \n   - It is often available in combination with other medications, such as acetaminophen or ibuprofen.\n\n2. **Norco**: \n   - This is a specific brand name for a combination medication that contains hydrocodone and acetaminophen.\n   - It is prescribed for pain relief and is formulated in specific strengths, typically containing 5 mg, 7.5 mg, or 10 mg of hydrocodone per tablet, along with 325 mg of acetaminophen.\n\nIn summary, hydrocodone is the active opioid ingredient, while Norco is a brand name medication that includes hydrocodone along with acetaminophen. Always consult with a healthcare provider for advice on medications and their appropriate use.",
